CNAME File – Custom Domain Configuration

A CNAME file is a simple text file used for custom domain configuration on GitHub Pages, Netlify, Vercel, or other static hosting services.

---

📌 What is CNAME?

The CNAME file tells GitHub Pages (or your hosting provider) which custom domain your website should respond to. It contains exactly one line – your domain name.

---

🗂️ File Content

Create a file named CNAME (no file extension) in the root directory of your project with the following content:

```text
subhash7y.github.io
```

---

🔧 Customization

Replace subhash7y.github.io with your actual domain name based on your setup:

1. Default GitHub Pages Domain

```text
subhash7y.github.io
```

2. Custom Domain (Example)

```text
subhashkumar.com
```

3. Subdomain (Example)

```text
portfolio.subhashkumar.com
```

4. With WWW (Example)

```text
www.subhashkumar.com
```

---

📁 File Location

The CNAME file must be placed in:

```
Portfolio-Resume/
├── index.html
├── style.css
├── script.js
├── CNAME              ← Here (root of the repository)
├── README.md
├── LICENSE
└── ...
```

---

🚀 Deployment Notes

GitHub Pages

· Place the CNAME file in the root of your repository.
· Go to Settings → Pages and enter your domain in the "Custom domain" field.
· GitHub will automatically verify the domain.

Netlify

· You can also set the custom domain via Netlify Dashboard (Site settings → Domain management).
· The CNAME file is optional but recommended for portability.

Vercel

· Configure custom domains via Vercel Dashboard (Project settings → Domains).
· The CNAME file can also be used if needed.

---

✅ DNS Configuration (For Custom Domains)

If you're using a custom domain, you must also configure DNS records:

With GitHub Pages (Apex Domain - example.com)

Type Name Value
A @ 185.199.108.153
A @ 185.199.109.153
A @ 185.199.110.153
A @ 185.199.111.153

With GitHub Pages (WWW Subdomain)

Type Name Value
CNAME www subhash7y.github.io

With Netlify / Vercel

Follow your provider's DNS configuration guide.

---

🔍 Testing Your Domain

1. After setting the CNAME and DNS, wait up to 24 hours for propagation.
2. Visit your domain in a browser.
3. If it doesn't work, check:
   · DNS propagation status.
   · GitHub Pages custom domain settings.
   · SSL certificate (usually auto-provisioned).

---

⚠️ Important Notes

· The CNAME file must contain only the domain name – no https:// or trailing slashes.
· Keep the file content case-insensitive (lowercase is standard).
· If you change your domain, update both the CNAME file and hosting settings.
· Make sure the domain is correctly pointed to your hosting provider.

